{{More citations needed|date=February 2020}} {{Japanese Kofun |name = Tanomoshi Kofun |image = {{image requested|cat=Ōta, Gunma}} |alternate_name = Tanomoshi Ōtsukayama Kofun |location = {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōta, Gunma|ja|太田市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, near Ushizawa Town |coordinates = 36|coordinates = 15|coordinates = 32.0 |coordinates = 139|coordinates = 21|coordinates = 04.5 |size = Unknown, height 5.4 m |type = Unknown (hypothesized to be a {{ill|Zenpō-kōen-fun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref>Estimated based on the mound height of 5.4m</ref>) |built = Late 4th century<ref>Estimated based on excavated burial goods</ref> |burial = Unknown (likely pit-style) |burial goods = Three {{ill|Bronze mirrors|ja|銅鏡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, stone bracelets, 30 iron arrowheads, etc. }}
'''Tanomoshi Kofun''' (頼母子古墳) is an ancient Kofun ({{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) that was once located near Ushizawa Town, {{ill|Ōta, Gunma|ja|太田市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is also known as '''Tanomoshi Ōtsukayama Kofun''' (頼母子大塚山古墳).
== Overview ==
This kofun was once located west of the {{ill|Asakozuka Kofun|ja|朝子塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, south of the typeer {{ill|National Route 354 (Japan)|ja|国道354号|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (now {{ill|Gunma Prefectural Route 142|ja|群馬県道142号綿貫篠塚線|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). It is notable for the discovery of two {{ill|Sankakuen Shinjūkyō|ja|三角縁神獣鏡|1=Triangular-Rimmed Divine Beast Mirror|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (triangular-rimmed deity and beast mirrors), the second-highest number found in {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, following a discovery in 1915 at a kofun in {{ill|Mihongi, Fujioka|ja|藤岡市三本木|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>Similar discoveries were made at {{ill|Shibasaki Kanisawa Kofun|ja|柴崎蟹沢古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Takasaki, Gunma|ja|高崎市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Maebashi Tenjinyama Kofun|ja|前橋天神山古墳|1=Maebashi Tenjinyama Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Maebashi|ja|前橋市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.</ref>
The mound was destroyed in **1910 (Meiji 43)** for soil extraction. Based on census records and the burial goods found, it is considered **the predecessor to the Asakozuka Kofun’s chief burial**. The burial chamber is believed to have been a **clay coffin-style (nendokaku)**.
== area ==
The only surviving measurement of the kofun is its mound height:
* Mound height: **5.4** [[meter|m]]
== burial goods ==
During the 1910 excavation, the following burial goods were discovered: - **Three bronze mirrors**: ** **Ripple-pattern dragon and tiger mirror (波紋帯龍虎鏡)** ** **Gosaku-inscribed belt mirror with three deities and five beasts (吾作銘帯三神五獣鏡)** ** **Inscribed belt mirror with four deities and four beasts (有銘文帯四神四獣鏡)** - **Stone bracelets** - **Iron arrowheads** (approximately 30)
The **whereabouts of the Gosaku-inscribed mirror and the inscribed four-deity mirror are currently unknown**.
== Gosaku-Inscribed Belt Mirror with Three Deities and Five Beasts ==
A rubbing of this mirror, presumed to be the one from this kofun, is stored at the **Nara Prefectural Tenri Library**{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}, and a replica is preserved at the **Anthropology Museum of Nanzan University**.
The mirror is now attributed to an excavation in **Tsuchida, {{ill|Kani, Gifu|ja|可児市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Gifu Prefecture**, and is **from the same mold as mirrors discovered at**: - **{{ill|Saikumezuka Kofun|ja|西求女塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}** (Hyōgo Prefecture) - **{{ill|Tsubai Ōtsukayama Kofun|ja|椿井大塚山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}** (Kyoto Prefecture) - **{{ill|Shiroyama No.1 Kofun (Katori, Chiba)|ja|城山1号墳 (香取市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}** (Chiba Prefecture)
