'''Tanomoshi Kofun''' (頼母子古墳) is an ancient Kofun ({{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun|qq=}}) that was once located near Ushizawa Town, {{ill|Ōta, Gunma|ja|太田市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōta, Gunma|qq=}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gunma Prefecture|qq=}}. It is also known as '''Tanomoshi Ōtsukayama Kofun''' (頼母子大塚山古墳).
== Overview ==
This kofun was once located west of the {{ill|Asakozuka Kofun|ja|朝子塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asakozuka Kofun|qq=}}, south of the typeer {{ill|National Route 354 (Japan)|ja|国道354号|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 354 (Japan)|qq=}} (now {{ill|Gunma Prefectural Route 142|ja|群馬県道142号綿貫篠塚線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gunma Prefectural Route 142|qq=}}). It is notable for the discovery of two {{ill|Sankakuen Shinjūkyō|ja|三角縁神獣鏡|1=Triangular-Rimmed Divine Beast Mirror|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sankakuen Shinjūkyō|13=User:Immanuelle/Triangular-Rimmed Divine Beast Mirror|qq=}} (triangular-rimmed deity and beast mirrors), the second-highest number found in {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gunma Prefecture|qq=}}, following a discovery in 1915 at a kofun in {{ill|Mihongi, Fujioka|ja|藤岡市三本木|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mihongi, Fujioka|qq=}}.<ref>Similar discoveries were made at {{ill|Shibasaki Kanisawa Kofun|ja|柴崎蟹沢古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibasaki Kanisawa Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Takasaki, Gunma|ja|高崎市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takasaki, Gunma|qq=}} and {{ill|Maebashi Tenjinyama Kofun|ja|前橋天神山古墳|1=Maebashi Tenjinyama Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Maebashi Tenjinyama Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Maebashi Tenjinyama Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Maebashi|ja|前橋市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Maebashi|qq=}}.</ref>
The mound was destroyed in **1910 (Meiji 43)** for soil extraction. Based on census records and the burial goods found, it is considered **the predecessor to the Asakozuka Kofun’s chief burial**. The burial chamber is believed to have been a **clay coffin-style (nendokaku)**.
== area ==
The only surviving measurement of the kofun is its mound height:
* Mound height: **5.4** [[meter|m]]
== burial goods ==
During the 1910 excavation, the following burial goods were discovered: - **Three bronze mirrors**: ** **Ripple-pattern dragon and tiger mirror (波紋帯龍虎鏡)** ** **Gosaku-inscribed belt mirror with three deities and five beasts (吾作銘帯三神五獣鏡)** ** **Inscribed belt mirror with four deities and four beasts (有銘文帯四神四獣鏡)** - **Stone bracelets** - **Iron arrowheads** (approximately 30)
The **whereabouts of the Gosaku-inscribed mirror and the inscribed four-deity mirror are currently unknown**.
== Gosaku-Inscribed Belt Mirror with Three Deities and Five Beasts ==
A rubbing of this mirror, presumed to be the one from this kofun, is stored at the **Nara Prefectural Tenri Library**{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}, and a replica is preserved at the **Anthropology Museum of Nanzan University**.
The mirror is now attributed to an excavation in **Tsuchida, {{ill|Kani, Gifu|ja|可児市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kani, Gifu|qq=}}, Gifu Prefecture**, and is **from the same mold as mirrors discovered at**: - **{{ill|Saikumezuka Kofun|ja|西求女塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saikumezuka Kofun|qq=}}** (Hyōgo Prefecture) - **{{ill|Tsubai Ōtsukayama Kofun|ja|椿井大塚山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsubai Ōtsukayama Kofun|qq=}}** (Kyoto Prefecture) - **{{ill|Shiroyama No.1 Kofun (Katori, Chiba)|ja|城山1号墳 (香取市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiroyama No.1 Kofun (Katori, Chiba)|qq=}}** (Chiba Prefecture)
